{{Politics of Egypt}}

The '''Egyptian Revolution of 2013''', locally called the '''June 30 Revolution''' ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]:<U+062B><U+0648><U+0631><U+0629> <U+0663><U+0660> <U+064A><U+0648><U+0646><U+064A><U+0648>) and also referred to as the '''Second Egyptian Revolution''' by several international media outlets,{{#tag:ref|See <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/03/mohamed-morsi-egypt-second-revolution|title=Mohamed Morsi ousted in Egypt's second revolution in two years|date=July 4, 2013|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/egypt-struggles-with-political-chaos-after-second-revolution-a-913674.html|title=Egypt Struggles With Political Chaos After Second Revolution|date=July 29, 2013|publisher=Der Spiegel}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/thousands-gather-celebrate-egypt-second-revolution/1696926.html|title=Thousands Gather to Celebrate Egypt's 'Second Revolution'|date=July 7, 2013|publisher=Voice of America}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/e341452a-e574-11e2-ad1a-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2Fe341452a-e574-11e2-ad1a-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Dintl&siteedition=intl&_i_referer=#axzz2p526eK3V|title=Egypt: The second revolution|date=July 5, 2013|publisher=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/politics/2013/07/egypt-morsi-ouster-blow-turkey.html|title=Egypt<U+2019>s Second Revolution a Blow to Turkey|date=July 15, 2013|publisher=Al-Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.de/revolution-in-egypt-again/a-16928333|title=Revolution in Egypt, again|date=July 4, 2013|publisher=DW}}</ref>}} was a mass revolt that erupted in [[Egypt]] on 30 June 2013, marking the one-year anniversary of [[Mohamed Morsi]]'s [[Egyptian presidential election, 2012|inauguration as president]]. Millions of protesters across Egypt took to the streets and demanded the immediate resignation of the president.<ref name=reuters30June>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/30/us-egypt-protests-idUSBRE95Q0NO20130630|title=Millions flood Egypt's streets to demand Mursi quit|date=30 June 2013|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> The rallies were partly a response to [[Tamarod]], a grassroots movement that launched a petition in April earlier that year calling for the government to step down and it claimed to have collected more than 22 million signatures. The number of protesters is said to have ranged between 14 million to a strongly debatable and unlikely 33 million to be "the biggest protest in Egypt's history" according to military sources that claimed to have counted the numbers through helicopters that scanned the demonstrations' perimeters across the country.<ref name=reuters30June/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5ieTc_avmvfRH0r8OrMOgbYTXzPFA?docId=CNG.bf410fd2b50b272b32ae2b68b217fcea.441&hl=en|title=Millions flood Egypt streets to demand Morsi ouster|date=30 June 2013|publisher=AFP}}</ref>

Reasons for demanding Morsi's resignation include accusations of increasing authoritarianism and his pushing through an [[Islamist]] agenda disregarding the predominantly secular opposition or the rule of law.<ref name="Kingsley June 30">{{cite news|author=Patrick Kingsley| date=30 June 2013|title=Protesters across Egypt call for Mohamed Morsi to go|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/jun/30/mohamed-morsi-egypt-protests}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Egypt protests: Thousands gather at Tahrir Square to demand Morsi<U+2019>s ouster|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/world/2013/06/30/egypt_protests_thousands_gather_at_tahrir_square_to_demand_morsis_ouster.html|accessdate=30 June 2013|work=[[Associated Press|AP]] via ''[[Toronto Star]]''|date=30 June 2013|author=Hendawi, Hamza|author2=Macdonald, Alastair}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Spencer|first=Richard|title=Egypt protests: Army issues 48-hour ultimatum for agreement amid clashes|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/egypt/10152780/Egypt-protests-Army-issues-48-hour-ultimatum-for-agreement-amid-clashes.html|accessdate=1 July 2013|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=1 July 2013|location=Cairo}}</ref> The uprising concluded [[2012<U+2013>13 Egyptian protests|seven months of protests]] that started when the Morsi government issued a highly controversial [[2012 Draft Constitution of Egypt|draft constitution]] that gave him sweeping unlimited powers over the state's judicial system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/morsy-issues-new-constitutional-declaration|title=Morsy issues new constitutional declaration|date=22 November 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/egypt-at-a-crossroads-after-morsi-grants-himself-sweeping-powers-a-869291.html|title=Egypt at a Crossroads after Morsi Grants Himself Sweeping Powers|date=26 November  2012|publisher=Der Spiegel}}</ref> The demonstrations, which had started peacefully, turned violent when the headquarters of the Muslim Brotherhood were stormed in [[Mokattam]] in Cairo and when 5 members of the organization were killed amid clashes. At the same time, many [[Morsi]] supporters staged a relatively smaller rally in [[Rabaa Al-Adawiya Mosque|Rabaa al-Adawiya square]] in [[Nasr City]], a district of [[Cairo]].<ref name="BBC Crisis July 1">{{cite news|title=Egypt crisis: Mass protests over Morsi grip cities|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-23115821|accessdate=1 July 2013|publisher=BBC News|date=1 July 2013}}</ref> A total of 16 people were reported to have lost their lives and approximately 200 injured as of late Tuesday during the unrest as a result of clashes between pro and anti-Morsi demonstrators, according to the state-run news agency. Another 10 people were also reported to have been killed in the cities of [[Alexandria]], [[Marsa Matruh]] and [[Minya, Egypt|Minya]].<ref name="CNN-Showdown?">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/07/02/world/meast/egypt-protests/|title=Showdown? Egypt's Morsy defies military 'ultimatum'|date=3 July 2013|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref name="BBC-Coup">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-23173794|title=Egypt crisis: Army ousts President Mohammed Morsi|date=3 July 2013|publisher=BBC}}</ref>

On 1 July, amid the chaos the country was facing, the military delivered a nationwide TV and radio statement giving both the government and the opposition a 48-hour ultimatum to resolve the political crisis and meet the people's demands or it would intervene to restore order.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/75414.aspx|title=Egyptian military gives 48 hour ultimatum to Brotherhood, political forces|date=1 July 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/07/01/world/meast/egypt-protests/index.html?hpt=hp_t1|title=Egypt's military gives Morsy ultimatum|date=2 July 2013|publisher=CNN}}</ref> The following day, Morsi delivered an evening speech where he declared his rejection of the declaration claiming he was the elected president who represented the will of the people. The same day, another statement was released on the official [[Facebook]] page of the [[Supreme Council of the Armed Forces]] titled "The Final Hours" that read: "We swear by God that we are ready to sacrifice our blood for Egypt and its people against any terrorist, extremist or fool".<ref name="CNN-Showdown?"/>

On the night of 3 July, General [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]], head of the Egyptian Armed Forces, announced in a live televised address that Mohamed Morsi [[2013 Egyptian coup d'<U+00E9>tat|had been deposed]] and replaced by the head of the constitutional court [[Adly Mansour]] and that the constitution had been suspended.<ref name="BBC-Coup"/> Morsi was immediately detained and kept under house arrest at the Republican Guard headquarters in Cairo while several other government officials and Islamist figures supporting Morsi were also arrested.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/president-morsi-ousted-democratically-elected-leader-house-arrest/story?id=19568447|title=President Morsi Ousted: First Democratically Elected Leader Under House Arrest|date=3 July 2013|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> The move was widely deemed as a "coup" and it marked a turning point for the country's future and for the fate of the [[Muslim Brotherhood]], as it was designated a terrorist group later that year in response to a [[December 2013 Mansoura bombing|bombing in Mansoura]] (though [[Ansar Bait al-Maqdis]] claimed responsibility)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/89992/Egypt/Politics-/Sinais-Ansar-Beit-AlMaqdis-claim-responsibility-fo.aspx|title=Sinai's Ansar Beit Al-Maqdis claim responsibility for Egypt's Mansoura blast|date=25 December 2013|publisher=Al Ahram}}</ref> and was subjected to an unprecedented crackdown amid an [[Islamist unrest in Egypt (2013<U+2013>present)|ongoing Islamist unrest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/90037.aspx|title=Egypt government declares Muslim Brotherhood 'terrorist group'|date=26 December 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/now-that-the-muslim-brotherhood-is-declared-a-terrorist-group-it-just-might-become-one/2014/01/10/268977d2-77d6-11e3-af7f-13bf0e9965f6_story.html|title=Now that the Muslim Brotherhood is declared a terrorist group, it just might become one|date=10 January 2014|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref>

==Background==
{{further|Egyptian Revolution of 2011|Egyptian constitutional referendum, 2011|Egyptian presidential election, 2012}}
Amid growing anger towards the regime, President [[Hosni Mubarak]], whose reign was marked by increasing corruption and authoritarianism, resigned on 11 February 2011 following [[Timeline of the Egyptian Revolution of 2011|18 days of mass protests]] that marked the beginning of a new era of political instability in Egypt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/feb/11/hosni-mubarak-resigns-egypt-cairo|title=Hosni Mubarak resigns <U+2013> and Egypt celebrates a new dawn|date=February 11, 2011|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> The subsequent transitional period, which saw the [[Supreme Council of the Armed Forces]] (SCAF) taking power under Field Marshal [[Mohamed Hussein Tantawi]] immediately after Mubarak's ouster, saw [[Timeline of the 2011<U+2013>12 Egyptian civil unrest under the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces|renewed deadly clashes]] and [[Human rights in Egypt under the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces|human rights abuses]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/26220.aspx|title=SCAF: A brief history of injustice|date=November 10, 2011|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> A round of elections started to take place in the country starting with the [[Egyptian constitutional referendum, 2011|2011 referendum]], in which a majority approved of reforms drafted by a [[Egyptian constitutional review committee of 2011|military-formed committee]]. The election however proved to be highly controversial despite some positive reforms such limiting the president's time in office to two four-year terms. Many opposition figures and activists were upset with the reforms as they were drafted in just ten days and were offered to the public for only three weeks before the referendum. Leading figures such as [[Amr Moussa]] and [[Mohamed ElBaradei]] wanted a new constitution to be drawn up from scratch before any elections are held, which would have occurred in case of a "no" vote. However, two of the country's largest political forces back then, the [[Muslim Brotherhood]] and remnants of the former [[National Democratic Party (Egypt)|National Democratic Party]], have endorsed the reforms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12763313|title=Q&A: Egypt's constitutional referendum|date=March 17, 2011|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/jun/12/egypt-a-constitution-first|title=Egypt: a constitution first|date=June 12, 2011|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> This turnout proved highly beneficial for the Brotherhood in the following months as they achieved nearly all of their political ambitions including a majority win for the Islamist current in the [[Egyptian parliamentary election, 2011<U+2013>12|2011<U+2013>12 parliamentary election]], during which the Brotherhood was accused by many opposition figures of making deals with the military while protesters [[November 2011 Cairo clashes|were being killed]] by security forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/31403/Egypt/Politics-/Details-emerge-about-a-SCAF-deal-with-parties-duri.aspx|title=Details emerge about a SCAF 'deal' with parties during Mohamed Mahmoud clashes |date=January 10, 2012|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/amb-marc-ginsberg/unholy-alliance-egypts-mi_b_1109534.html|title=Unholy Alliance: Egypt's Military & The Muslim Brotherhood|date=November 23, 2011|publisher=The Huffington Post}}</ref> Their efforts culminated with [[Mohamed Morsi]] winning against [[Ahmed Shafik]] by 51.7% in the [[Egyptian presidential election, 2012|2012 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/06/24/us-egypt-election-idUSBRE85G01U20120624|title=Islamist joy as Morsy elected Egypt president|date=June 24, 2012|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>

===Constituent Assembly of 2012===
{{main|Egyptian Constituent Assembly of 2012}}
In April, a couple of months prior to Morsi's inauguration, the Administrative Court suspended a constituent assembly previously appointed in March without giving any clear reasons for this decision and which the Brotherhood claimed was politically-motivated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-17665048|title=Egypt court suspends constitutional assembly|date=April 10, 2012|publisher=BBC}}</ref> In mid-June however, another [[Egyptian Constituent Assembly of 2012|100-member assembly]] was officially selected a week after a deal was reached between the ruling military council and representatives of 22 parties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-18360403|title=Egypt parties end deadlock over constitutional panel|date=June 8, 2012|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/44696.aspx|title=Official: The 100 members of Egypt's revamped Constituent Assembly|date=June 12, 2012|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> Tensions later resumed after a court ruled that the entire Islamist-dominated parliament was illegally elected and ordered the body to dissolve, which angered the Brotherhood and [[Mohamed Beltagy]] called it a "full-fledged coup".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/egypt-court-rules-entire-parliament-illegally-elected-orders-body-to-dissolve-after-unconstitutional-vote/|title=Egypt court rules entire parliament illegally elected, orders body to dissolve after unconstitutional vote|date=June 14, 2012|publisher=CBS News}}</ref> On 18 June, the SCAF issued a supplementary constitutional declaration that limits the to-be president's power over the military and gives it complete control over all army decisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-18494178|title=Q&A: Egypt's new constitutional declaration|date=June 18, 2012|publisher=BBC}}</ref> However, those controversial moves never changed the status of the constituent assembly as it was elected by the [[Shura Council]] not by parliament. Also, the same day the military delivered its statement, [[Hossam El-Gheriany]] was elected as chairman of the assembly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/45508/Egypt/Politics-/UPDATE-Eminent-judge-ElGhariani-named-head-of-cont.aspx|title=Eminent judge El-Ghariani named head of contested Constituent Assembly|date=June 18, 2012|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> Military chief Mohamed Hussein Tantawi was forced to retire by Morsi on 12 August, a month and a half after the latter was elected and a week after [[August 2012 Sinai attack|a militant attack in Sinai]] that had the military preoccupied, leaving the constituent assembly's drafting process unchallenged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/aug/12/egyptian-defence-chief-ousted-shakeup|title=Egypt defence chief Tantawi ousted in surprise shakeup|date=August 13, 2013|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>

===Morsi's declaration and aftermath===
{{further|2012 Draft Constitution of Egypt|2012<U+2013>13 Egyptian protests}}
{{Expand section|date=January 2014}}<!--A fair description of how controversial the declaration was and the following protests in November-->

===Tamarod campaign===
{{main|Tamarod}}
Amid a climate of dissent and division, '''Tamarod''' (Arabic for "rebellion"), a grassroots movement, was founded in April 2013 by five young activists with ages ranging between 22 and 30 years old. They orchestrated a door-to-door, street-level campaign collecting signatures from Egyptians across the country calling for, among other demands, President Morsi<U+2019>s resignation, early presidential elections and the start of a renewed constituent process.<ref name="Jadaliyya Tamarod">{{cite web|url=http://www.jadaliyya.com/pages/index/12516/tamarod_egypts-revolution-hones-its-skills|title=Tamarod: Egypt's Revolution Hones its Skills|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Jadaliyya}}</ref> Tamarod was supported by various opposition parties and autonomous social movements.  The campaign, reminiscent of 1919<U+2019>s collection of petitions [[Egyptian Revolution of 1919|against British occupation]], called for massive protests all over the country on 30 June 2013, which was the first anniversary of Morsi's inauguration, to create popular pressure on the government to see through their demands. The campaign<U+2019>s leading members [[Mahmoud Badr]], [[Hassan Shahin]], [[Mohamed Abdel Aziz (activist)|Mohamed Abdel Aziz]], [[Mai Wahba]] and [[Mohamed Heikal (activist)|Mohamed Heikal]], initially unfamiliar to the public, started to continuously gain strong popularity among Egyptians reflected in the people<U+2019>s eagerness to publicly register their names, ID card numbers and signatures on the petition form.<ref name="Jadaliyya Tamarod"/> The movement was also intensifying its political activity, uniting all anti-Brotherhood parties and most political factions in its mission. Among the groups supporting it were the [[National Salvation Front (Egypt)|National Salvation Front]], the [[Kefaya|Kefaya Movement]] and the [[April 6 Youth Movement]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Reactions vary to the Rebel movement's 30 June plans|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/06/05/reactions-vary-to-tamarods-30-june-plans/|agency=Daily News Egypt|date=June 5, 2013}}</ref> These also included members of the former National Democratic Party who, as stated by [[Mohamed ElBaradei]], were allowed to participate as long as they weren<U+2019>t convicted of any crimes such as Morsi's 2012 rival candidate [[Ahmed Shafik]] who supported the protests.<ref>{{cite news|title=Egypt opposition opens to former autocrat's party|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2013/06/22/Egypt-opposition-opens-to-former-autocrat-s-party.html|agency=Al-Arabiya|date=June 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tamarod clarifies Shafiq endorsement|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/05/18/tamarod-clarifies-shafiq-endorsement/|agency=Daily News Egypt|date=May 18, 2013}}</ref> However, the presidency and its supporters had a different reaction to Tamarod which was far from appeasing the population. A counter-campaign called "Tagarod" (Arabic for "impartiality") was started by [[Al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya]] member [[Assem Abdel Maged]], who called on Morsi's supporters to sign this petition to keep the "legitimately elected president in his post".<ref>{{cite news|title=Tagarod campaign to counter Tamarod|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/05/13/tagarod-campaign-to-counter-tamarod/|agency=Daily News Egypt|date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> Abdel Maged's campaign however, proved unsuccessful in terms of impact compared to Tamarod which was able to penetrate and mobilize the "[[Couch Party]]", the silent majority of Egyptians who usually avoid participating in political events but prominently joined anti-Morsi demonstrations this time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.al-akhbar.com/node/16279|title=Egypt<U+2019>s Tamarrud: A Revolution for the Lazy?|date=June 29, 2013|publisher=Al Akhbar}}</ref> The movement's effectiveness in sparking the uprising against Morsi had organizations like the ''[[Washington Institute for Near East Policy]]'' dubbing the events as the "Tamarod Revolution".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/about/campaign/egypts-tamarod-revolution-faq|title=Egypt's Tamarod Revolution: A Video FAQ|publisher=Washington Institute for Near East Policy}}</ref> Not only this, but it directly inspired many other copycat campaigns throughout the Arab world such as [[Gaza]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/politics/2013/10/gaza-tamarod-protests-oust-hamas.html|title=Gaza<U+2019>s Tamarod Calls for Nov. 11 Protests to Oust Hamas|date=October 9, 2013|publisher=Al-Monitor}}</ref> [[Morocco]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/moroccos-islamists-rescued-from-early-elections|title=Morocco's Islamists Rescued from Early Elections|date=September 6, 2013|publisher=Washington Institute for Near East Policy}}</ref> [[Tunisia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://northafricapost.com/4075-tunisia-condemns-its-version-of-tamarod.html|title=Tunisia condemns its version of Tamarod|date=July 23, 2013|publisher=The North Africa Post}}</ref> and [[Yemen]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/07/yemen-divided-egypt-crisis-morsi.html|title=Yemen Divided Over Egypt|date=July 12, 2013|publisher=Al-Monitor}}</ref> as well as [[Bahrain Tamarod|a new wave of protests]] in [[Bahrain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/menasource/bahrain-in-egypt-s-shadow|title=Bahrain in Egypt<U+2019>s Shadow|date=September 27, 2013|publisher=Atlantic Council}}</ref>

===Allegations of previous military involvement ===
Egypt's [[Egyptian Armed Forces|military]] has long showed discontent at Morsi's policies and viewed the political tensions between the government and its opponents as a threat to the nation's stability.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/72030.aspx|title=Sinai crisis heightens tension between Egypt president, army chief: Sources|date=May 21, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref><ref name="Huff Post Sisi June 23">{{cite news|title=Egypt Morsi Protests: Army Ready To Save Nation From 'Dark Tunnel,' Defense Minister Says |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/23/egypt-morsi-protests-army-ready-to-save-nation-dark-tunnel_n_3486903.html|agency=AP|date=23 June 2013}}</ref> This had had come to light following a huge Islamist rally in support of the [[Syrian Civil War|Syrian uprising]] sponsored by the Brotherhood in [[Cairo Stadium]]. The conference was meant to warn those hoping to push Mohamed Morsi out of office, and was aimed at forging stronger ties with extremist Islamist groups. Morsi shocked the nation then by cutting diplomatic ties with [[Syria]] and by remaining silent while hardliners were calling for jihad to combat the Syrian regime and [[Shiite]] fighters and when they were using sectarian speech towards Shiite Muslims. What worried the army though, is that Morsi, while not explicitly calling himself for holy war, delivered a speech in which he called for a foreign intervention against [[Bashar al-Assad]]'s government by establishing a [[no-fly zone]] over Syria. The military responded by issuing a statement where it argued that its only role is to guard Egypt's borders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/75564/Egypt/Politics-/Morsi-role-at-Syria-rally-seen-as-tipping-point-fo.aspx|title=Morsi role at Syria rally seen as tipping point for Egypt army|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/world/2013/06/15/syria_egypts_morsi_cuts_diplomatic_ties_calls_for_nofly_zone.html|title=Syria: Egypt<U+2019>s Morsi cuts diplomatic ties, calls for no-fly zone|date=June 15, 2013|publisher=Toronto Star}}</ref>

On 23 June, [[General]] [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]] issued a statement warning all sides saying that the [[Egyptian Army|army]] will not allow the country to fall into a <U+201C>dark tunnel of conflict<U+201D>. He also added:<ref name="Huff Post Sisi June 23"/>
<blockquote>"Those who think that we (the military) are oblivious to the dangers that threaten the Egyptian state are mistaken. We will not remain silent while the country slips into a conflict that will be hard to control"</blockquote>

After Morsi was ousted on July 3, most of the country's energy crises, that were very common during Morsi's presidency, were surprisingly diminished following the coup d'<U+00E9>tat. ''[[The New York Times]]'' (NYT) claims there might have been a campaign orchestrated by members of the old Mubarak regime and top military generals that was meant to undermine Mohamed Morsi's one-year rule. The reason for this belief is that state agencies responsible for providing electricity and ensuring gas supplies failed so fundamentally so gas lines and [[rolling blackouts]] fueled widespread anger at the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/11/world/middleeast/improvements-in-egypt-suggest-a-campaign-that-undermined-morsi.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Sudden Improvements in Egypt Suggest a Campaign to Undermine Morsi|date=July 10, 2013|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> NYT also claims that a smear media campaign against Morsi, that began immediately following Morsi's inauguration, helped feed popular discontent towards the authorities by adopting a contradictory stance through favoring the military while honoring Morsi's position as president of the republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/14/world/middleeast/president-morsi-of-egypt-is-undercut-by-state-run-media.html|title=Egypt<U+2019>s New President Is Being Undercut by State-Run Media|date=July 13, 2012|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>

==Preparation and security precautions==
During security measures in [[Upper Egypt]], the [[Luxor]] security directorate announced that it had transferred all those jailed in the local police station to Qena prison as a mean of avoiding the 2011 scenario due to the risk of violence. [[Aswan]] saw heavy security presence and the police chief announced that he will personally head the operation room to receive complaints and information during the demonstrations and said that security personnel will protect their stations as well as state property, and added that the people will be protected, not the regime or any political party. Members of the FJP have gathered in front of their party headquarters to secure the complex. These procedures took place on June 30, the day of protests.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live">{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/75297.aspx|title=Live updates: Millions join anti-Morsi protests in Egypt|date=30 June 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref><ref name="Aswat Masriya updates">{{cite web|url=http://en.aswatmasriya.com/news/view.aspx?id=2cddf5c7-9402-4b14-8920-9e0d8da52e0c|title=Updates on protests against Mursi after his first year in office|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Aswat Masriya}}</ref><ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2">{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/75341.aspx|title=Live updates 2: Millions on streets for anti-Morsi protests; 4 dead in Upper Egypt|date=30 June 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref>

According to information that came out after the removal of Morsi, officials claimed that Morsi stopped working at the [[Egyptian Presidential Palace|presidential office]] as early as June 26 in anticipation to the protests and moved with his family to [[Koubbeh Palace]], just a few blocks away from the main palace.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hendawi|first=Hamza|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/his-final-days-morsi-was-isolated-defiant|title=In his final days, Morsi was isolated but defiant|publisher=Associated Press|date=July 4, 2013}}</ref>

===Fears of violence against Copts===
Weeks prior to the protests, [[Coptic Christians]], particularly in [[Upper Egypt]], received threats from Morsi's Islamist supporters, pressuring them not to take part in the protests. Sheikh Essam Abdulamek, a member of parliament's [[Shura Council]], said in an interview on television that Christians should not participate in the protests and warned them "do not sacrifice your children [since the] general Muslim opinion will not be silent about the ousting of the president." Letters were delivered to Christian families in [[Minya]] where they were threatened not to join the protests, otherwise their "businesses, cars, homes, schools, and churches" might "catch fire".<ref name="Human Events">{{cite web|url=http://www.humanevents.com/2013/07/03/pro-morsi-terrorists-threaten-christians-against-protesting/|title=Pro-Morsi forces threaten Christians against protesting|publisher=Human Events|date=July 3, 2013}}</ref> The letters, signed by "Peaple zealous of the nation", read:
<blockquote>"If you are not worried about any of these, then worry about your children and your homes. This message is being delivered with tact. But when the moment of truth comes, there will be no tact."<ref name="Human Events"/></blockquote>
There have been incitements against Copts by some of Morsi's staunchest allies such as [[Al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya]]'s leading hardline cleric [[Assem Abdel Maged]] directly threatened the country's Christian community by saying "if you go down into the streets on 30 June, you will bring black days onto yourselves." President Mohamed Morsi himself invited [[Pope Tawadros II of Alexandria|Pope Tawadros II]] to a meeting at the country's presidential palace in what has been seen as an attempt to put pressure on him while the pope told Morsi to do what is necessary to bring the nation together and work for the peace of Egypt, not to stir up quarrels. "I am still hoping to see improvements in the economic and social life of the country," he said, while Morsi suggested that the church should advise Egypt<U+2019>s Christian community not to participate in the protests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/News/3146/17/Egypt%E2%80%99s-Copts-defiant-.aspx|title=Egypt<U+2019>s Copts defiant|date=June 17, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> Another pro-Morsi cleric [[Safwat Hegazi]] addressed the country's Christians by saying:"You share this country with us, but there are red lines, and one red line is the legitimacy of Dr. Morsi. Whoever splashes water on that, we will spill his blood."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/06/20/19042756-egypts-coptic-christians-say-they-are-no-longer-safe?lite|title=Egypt's Coptic Christians say they are 'no longer safe'|date=June 20, 2013|publisher=NBC News}}</ref>

==Early events==

===June 28===
[[File:Anti Morsi protest march at 28th June 2013.jpg|thumb|Anti-Morsi demonstrators marching in Cairo on June 28]]
On Friday 28 June, protests against Morsi started to build throughout Egypt including in such cities as [[Cairo]], [[Alexandria]], [[Dakahlia Governorate|Dakahlia]], [[Gharbiya]] and [[Aswan]] as a "warm up" for the massive protests expected on 30 June that were planned by Tamarod. Pro-Morsi and Muslim Brotherhood supporters started counterdemonstrations at the [[Rabia Al-Adawiya Mosque]] in Nasr City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/75483.aspx |title=Egypt warms up for a decisive day of anti- and pro-Morsi protests |publisher=English.ahram.org.eg |date=7 February 2013 |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref>

===June 29===
Deadly clashes broke out this day in several Egyptian cities, most notably [[Alexandria]], where armed confrontations between Morsi's supporters and his opponents, with both sides in the fighting armed with different kinds of firearms, left many injured and three dead, a 14-year old boy, a member of the Muslim Brotherhood who was shot dead and an American student, Andrew Pochter, was killed after being stabbed in the chest during an anti-Morsi rally. Protesters stormed the headquarters of the Muslim Brotherhood's ruling [[Freedom and Justice Party (Egypt)|Freedom and Justice Party]] (FJP) and set the building ablaze.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/06/egypt-violence-ahead-of-june-30-protests.html#|title=Deadly Violence Breaks out in Egypt Ahead of June 30 Protests|date=June 29, 2013|publisher=Al-Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/us-student-stabbed-to-death-during-egypt-protests-was-in-the-country-teaching-children-english-8679669.html|title=US student stabbed to death during Egypt protests was in the country teaching children English|date=June 29, 2013|publisher=The Independent}}</ref> In [[Port Said]], a bomb detonated in the city's Martyrs Square where protesters had gathered to protest against Mohamed Morsi. The explosion, which ''[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]'' reported to have been a hand-grenade thrown by unidentified men, injured 14 demonstrators and killed a journalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/06/29/explosion-rocks-port-said-killing-journalist/|title=Explosion rocks Port Said, killing journalist|date=June 29, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> A police general in Sinai was gunned down by militants in an ambush when he was leaving his car, before they ran away.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/75259.aspx|title=June 29, 2013|date=June 29, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref>

In Cairo, the president's opponents started building up in anticipation for June 30's uprising as thousands of anti-Morsi demonstrators took to [[Tahrir Square]] with the number of tents increasing to 150. At the presidential palace, protesters set up 18 tents and erected a stage at the entrance of [[Heliopolis Sporting Club]]. Five [[Central Security Forces|CSF]] trucks and a fire-fighting vehicle went to reside in the location as a security precaution.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 29 protests">{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/75217/Egypt/Politics-/Protesters-around-Cairo-build-up-sitins-for--June.aspx|title=Protesters around Cairo build up sit-ins for 30 June|date=June 29, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> This day, Tamarod claimed to have collected more than 22 million signatures their petition caling for Morsi to step down. The numbers were announced in a press conference statement in which the group's leaders described the 30 June protests as a new wave of the 2011 revolution that and stressed that "Morsy has lost legitimacy after millions of signatures calling for his removal were collected, and after he refused to respect the constitution and the law". The statement also urged protesters to remain peaceful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/tamarod-petition-has-22-million-signatures|title=Tamarod petition has 22 million signatures|date=June 29, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref> On the other hand, thousands staged an open-ended rally since Friday which was called for by 40 Islamist parties and groups led by the FJP and was held under the banner "Democratic legitimacy is a red line".<ref name="Al-Ahram June 29 protests"/>

==Timeline==

===June 30: Revolution Day===
{{Expand section|date=January 2014}}<!--Whole paragraph(s) needed about death toll and overall number of protesters in each location that day-->
The much anticipated day begins with several marches throughout [[Cairo]] on Sunday heading to either [[Tahrir Square]] or [[Heliopolis Palace|Ittihadiya Palace]] with other comparatively smaller protests taking place at [[Rabaa Al-Adawiya Mosque|Rabaa al-Adawiya square]], where pro-Morsi demonstrators are mainly centered, and another around the Ministry of Culture in [[Zamalek]] with artists and intellectuals staging a sit-in chanting against the Morsi-appointed Culture Minister. The [[30 June Front]] announced that open-ended sit-ins have been staged in Tahrir and across the country until President Mohamed Morsi steps down and until the people's legitimate demands have been answered.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/> Tahrir started filling with protesters as early as 8:00 AM with street emptied of traffic and nearly all shops were closed for the day. The people started chanting "Down, down with the rule of the Morshed (Supreme Guide of the Muslim Brotherhood)" and "He will leave, we won't leave".<ref name="WSJ June 30 Live">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/middleeast/2013/06/30/live-egypt-protests/|title=Live: Egypt Protests|date=30 June 2013|publisher=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> By 11:00 AM, thousands had already gathered in the square and organizers claimed in advance the support of millions to come.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/middle-east-live/2013/jun/30/egypt-mohamed-morsi-protests-live|title=Egypt's Mohamed Morsi faces mass protests: live updates|date=30 June 2013|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> Two main marches that headed to Tahrir came from [[Giza]] with tens of thousands rallying along [[Dokki]]'s Tahrir Street joined by opposition leader [[Hamdeen Sabahi]] and prominent filmmaker [[Khaled Youssef]]. The march later merged with another in [[Al Nahda square]] near [[Cairo University]] led by [[Mohamed ElBaradei]] forming the bigger "Mostafa Mahmoud march" that later reached Tahrir Square at around 18:10 PM with the march's end still reportedly stretching back into Dokki. Other rallies that also arrived in Tahrir are the Dawaran Shubra march coming from [[Shubra]], the Maadi march who fist gathered in [[Maadi]]'s Horreya Square and several other marches whether organized or individual ones including the journalists' march led by current syndicate chairman [[Diaa Rashwan]] and former chairman [[Makram Mohammed Ahmed]] that began from the Press Syndicate headquarters in [[Downtown Cairo]].<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/> Later that day, the crowd in Tahrir Square has reached its maximum capacity of 500,000 demonstrators.<ref name="Kingsley June 30"/><ref name=reuters30June/> This prompted other joining protesters to fill up the square's neighboring alleys instead such as the nearby [[Talaat Harb Street]] and [[Qasr al-Nil Bridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2013/06/30/amazing-photos-of-egypts-massive-demonstrations/|title=Amazing photos of Egypt<U+2019>s massive demonstrations|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://elwatannews.com/news/details/213799|title=<U+0627><U+062D><U+062A><U+0634><U+0627><U+062F> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0645><U+062A><U+0638><U+0627><U+0647><U+0631><U+064A><U+0646> <U+0641><U+064A> <U+0637><U+0644><U+0639><U+062A> <U+062D><U+0631><U+0628> <U+0628><U+0639><U+062F> <U+0648><U+0635><U+0648><U+0644> <U+0645><U+0633><U+064A><U+0631><U+0629> <U+0643><U+0628><U+064A><U+0631><U+0629>.. <U+0648><U+0623><U+062D><U+062F> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0639><U+0627><U+0645><U+0644><U+064A><U+0646> <U+064A><U+0644><U+0642><U+064A> <U+0627><U+0644><U+062D><U+0644><U+0648><U+064A> <U+0639><U+0644><U+064A><U+0647><U+0645>|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Watan (Arabic)}}</ref> A less notable sit-in took place at the Culture Ministry in Zamalek's Shagarat al Dur Street with several artists including actors, musicians and painters who were banging clogs and were led by some intellectuals including [[Bahaa Taher]] who called for the toppling of the regime, and especially the newly appointed Islamist minister whom they accuse along with the Brotherhood of attempting to "Islamize" the country's cultural traditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/2013/06/29/Egyptian-artists-intellectuals-join-protest-for-Mursi-s-ouster.html|title=Egyptian artists, intellectuals join protest for Mursi<U+2019>s ouster|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Arabiya}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/5/35/75336/Arts--Culture/Stage--Street/Egypt-artists-stage-largest-protest-march-since-Ja.aspx|title=Egypt artists stage largest protest march since January 2011 revolution|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> They later headed to the [[Cairo Opera House]] to allegedly stage public performances and manifestations and they were expected to continue to Tahrir but it is unclear whether all of them went there or if some remained.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nileinternational.net/full_story.php?ID=88855|title=Artists Bring Their Touch to Egypt's 30 June Protests|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Nile TV}}</ref> In [[Shubra El-Kheima]], nearly 3,000 demonstrators, mostly women, formed [[human chain]]s extending over one kilometer and were organized by [[Egyptian Popular Current|Popular Current]] and the [[Constitution Party (Egypt)|Constitution Party]].<ref name="Al-Ahram Weekly June 30">{{cite web|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/News/3229/17/%E2%80%98Leave%E2%80%99.aspx|title=<U+2018>Leave<U+2019>|date=July 4, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram (Weekly)}}</ref> In addition, the [[April 6 Youth Movement]] and Constitution Party announced a sit-in in front of [[Abdeen Palace]] as soon as they received information that Prime Minister [[Hesham Qandil]] was there.<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/> Another thousand protesters gathered in front of the [[Koubbeh Palace|Qubba Palace]] only three kilometers away from Ittihadiya following rumors that Mohamed Morsi was residing there at the time, which was later semi-confirmed when the presidency announced it would hold a press conference at the palace later in the afternoon.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/> The [[satellite town]] of [[6th of October City|6th of October]] also saw hundreds rallying in Juhayna Square.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/news/end-morsi-breakdown-egypts-june-30-protest-502983|title=Is this the end for Morsi? A breakdown of Egypt's June 30 protest|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Bawaba}}</ref> Demonstrations have taken place in other similar locations around Cairo such as the wealthy district of [[New Cairo]], where several dozens have gathered in front of Morsi's residency waving Egyptian flags and red cards calling for his resignation while security forces deployed barriers to keep protesters away from the building.<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gate.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/13/70/366250/%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%8A/%D8%AA%D8%B8%D8%A7%D9%87%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A6%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A3%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B2%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D8%A6%D9%8A%D8%B3-%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%89-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B3.aspx|title=<U+062A><U+0638><U+0627><U+0647><U+0631> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0645><U+0626><U+0627><U+062A> <U+0623><U+0645><U+0627><U+0645> <U+0645><U+0646><U+0632><U+0644> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0631><U+0626><U+064A><U+0633> <U+0645><U+0631><U+0633><U+0649> <U+0628><U+0627><U+0644><U+062A><U+062C><U+0645><U+0639> <U+0627><U+0644><U+062E><U+0627><U+0645><U+0633>|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram (Arabic)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.youm7.com/News.asp?NewsID=1141947&#.UvGKLrSp2sZ|title=<U+0645><U+062A><U+0638><U+0627><U+0647><U+0631><U+0648><U+0646> <U+064A><U+0631><U+0641><U+0639><U+0648><U+0646> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0643><U+0627><U+0631><U+062A> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0623><U+062D><U+0645><U+0631> <U+0644><U+0644><U+0631><U+0626><U+064A><U+0633> <U+0623><U+0645><U+0627><U+0645> <U+0645><U+0646><U+0632><U+0644><U+0647> <U+0628><U+0627><U+0644><U+062A><U+062C><U+0645><U+0639>|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Youm7 (Arabic)}}</ref> This day, the main opposition [[National Salvation Front (Egypt)|National Salvation Front]] (NSF) issued a statement it called "Revolution Statement 1" and which goes:
<blockquote>"In the name of the Egyptian people with all their factions, the National Salvation Front announces public endorsement of the ouster of the regime of Mohamed Morsi and the Muslim Brotherhood," the statement reads.
		"The Egyptian population continue their revolution and will impose their will, which has become unequivocally clear in all Egypt's squares."
		"The Salvation Front also trusts that the Egyptian people will protect its revolution until peaceful transition of power is fulfilled...we also call on all political forces and all citizens to remain peaceful<U+2026>and refrain from dealing with the failed Brotherhood government until the fall of this tyrannical organisation."<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/><ref name="BBC Crisis July 1"/></blockquote>

[[File:Protestors issues Morsi a red card..jpg|thumb|left|Female protester waving a red card to Morsi in a demonstration on June 30, 2013]]
Although Morsi opponents had staged protest camps outside [[Heliopolis Palace|Ittihadiya Palace]], one of the country's main presidential palaces, in Cairo's [[Heliopolis (Cairo suburb)|Heliopolis]] suburb two days prior to the revolution, the number of protesters was relatively low with only a few hundred demonstrators present at the vicinity around 5:30 PM, compared to the huge masses staged in Tahrir Square and [[Sidi Gaber]] in Egypt's second city of [[Alexandria]] at the time. At the beginning, this was surprising to some who considered the location to be a second focal point of anti-Morsi protests in Cairo along with Tahrir. Most of the palace's gates were left unguarded except for gate 5 which saw a high concentration of armoured vehicles and police was nowhere to be seen but three were reportedly arrested by night in possession of weapons including blades and firearms, according to state news agency ''[[MENA (news)|MENA]]''.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/06/30/in-pictures-pro-morsi-rally-at-rabaa-al-adaweya/|title=In Pictures: Pro-Morsi Rally at Raba<U+2019>a Al-Adaweya|date=30 June 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> By 5:45 PM however, demonstrators started pouring in with tens of thousands coming individually or in rallies such as the march coming from [[El-Quba|Saray el-Qubba]] carrying Egyptian flags, red cards and waving banners of previously slain protesters such as [[Khalid Said]] while chanting anti-Morsi slogans, most notably ''"[[Ash-shab yurid isqat an-nizam|The people demand the fall of the regime]]"''.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/06/egyptians-demonstrate-in-large-numbers-against-morsi.html#|title=Millions of Egyptians Demand Morsi<U+2019>s Downfall|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Monitor}}</ref> At around 7:30 PM, the palace's surroundings were reportedly packed with protesters filling a broad boulevard for blocks and spilling into nearby avenues and ''Al-Ahram'' reported that the site was extremely crowded with even moving small distances taking a long time and according to the Health Ministry, one protester suffocated to death as a result of a [[Human crush|crowd crush]].<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/crowds-march-egypt-pushing-morsi-removal-154031220.html|title=Crowds march in Egypt, pushing for Morsi removal|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Yahoo News}}</ref><ref name="BBC MB HQ">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-23125387|title=Egypt protesters storm Muslim Brotherhood headquarters|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=BBC}}</ref> The demonstrations' mood was seemingly jovial with fireworks keeping the atmosphere upbeat and protesters cheering patrolling military helicopters the vicinity with laser lights.<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/egypt-protest-pictures-2013-6|title=These Photos Show Just How Massive The Protests In Egypt Have Become|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Business Insider}}</ref> ''[[MENA (news)|MENA]]'' reported that political forces present there announced that they will stage an open-ended sit-in till the president steps down.<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/>

Only five kilometers away from the presidential palace, Islamist supporters of Mohamed Morsi and the government held their huge sit-in at [[Rabaa Al-Adawiya Mosque|Rabaa al-Adawiya square]] in the [[Nasr City]] neighborhood of Cairo for a third consecutive day. They called their demonstration this day "Tagarod" as a counter name to the Tamarod campaign aimed at ousting Morsi.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref name="WSJ June 30 Live"/> The number of demonstrators was reportedly estimated at hundreds of thousands although the ruling Muslim Brotherhood-linked [[Freedom and Justice Party (Egypt)|Freedom and Justice Party]] (FJP) claimed on its Facebook page that the number was four million and a [[Shura Council]] member of the party had also claimed that the number of people in Rabaa al-Adawiya exceeded the numbers of anti-Morsi protesters in Cairo and all of Egypt. The number however, could not be verified as some experts ruled it out and said that the square and surrounding areas could hardly contain such a number.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.aswatmasriya.com/news/view.aspx?id=4e1319c4-46da-4cf1-acc2-67c8a1b5a062|title=FJP says Mursi supporters at Rabaa Adaweya are four million|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Aswat Masriya}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201307010657.html|title=Egypt: FJP Says Mursi Supporters At Rabaa Adaweya Are Four Million|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=allAfrica}}</ref> Most of them chanted for the protection of the president's democratic legitimacy while some believed that the president needed more time to deal with the country's difficulties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/06/30/world/africa/egypt-protests/|title=Morsy's foes, supporters face off in Egypt on his first anniversary|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=CNN}}</ref> The sit-in was prominently joined by the hardline Salafist group [[Al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya]] which called on the army and police to protect the president and, although initially wishing for non-violence to be exercised, threatened that if the police and army "fail to do their job in protecting the president<U+2019>s legitimacy <U+2026> we will do so ourselves,<U+201D> said Mohamed Hassan, the group's spokesman while refusing to clarify whether he implicated the group would use violence or not and also added that Al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya would not allow the overthrow of the democratically-elected president by any means.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/06/30/18-armed-men-arrested-on-cairo-alexandria-desert-road/|title=18 armed men arrested on Cairo-Alexandria desert road|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> However, the demonstrations continued peacefully with no reported clashes occurring between supporters and opponents of Morsi either at Rabaa al-Adawiya or at the presidential palace.<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/>

Egypt's second city of [[Alexandria]] saw protesters gathering at [[Al Qa'ed Ibrahim Mosque]], a meeting point for the city's rallies and also at the [[Sidi Gaber railway station|railway station]] in the neighborhood of [[Sidi Gaber]]. Hundreds of protesters had gathered by 4:35 PM, according to ''[[Al-Ahram]]'', but in the following few hours the square started filling with demonstrators who poured in from all over the coastal city in thousands, including hundreds of lawyers and court room officials heading from the Lawyers' Union headquarters toward the station, chanting "Leave! Leave!". By approximately 7:00 PM, the vicinity of the station was reportedly packed and people could hardly move. A sit-in was also declared with a stage and tents being erected, including a huge one near Omar al-Islam Mosque, as a preparation for the coming days.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elwatannews.com/news/details/213632|title=<U+0627><U+0646><U+0637><U+0644><U+0627><U+0642> <U+0645><U+0633><U+064A><U+0631><U+0627><U+062A> <U+0645><U+062D><U+0627><U+0645><U+064A><U+064A> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0625><U+0633><U+0643><U+0646><U+062F><U+0631><U+064A><U+0629> <U+0645><U+0646> <U+0645><U+0642><U+0631> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0646><U+0642><U+0627><U+0628><U+0629> <U+0625><U+0644><U+0649> "<U+0633><U+064A><U+062F><U+064A> <U+062C><U+0627><U+0628><U+0631>"|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=El-Watan (Arabic)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gate.ahram.org.eg/News/366006.aspx|title=<U+0627><U+0644><U+0645><U+062D><U+0627><U+0645><U+0648><U+0646> <U+0648><U+0645><U+0648><U+0638><U+0641><U+0648> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0645><U+062D><U+0627><U+0643><U+0645> <U+064A><U+062E><U+0631><U+062C><U+0648><U+0646> <U+0641><U+064A> <U+0645><U+0633><U+064A><U+0631><U+0627><U+062A> <U+062D><U+0627><U+0634><U+062F><U+0629> <U+0645><U+0646> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0645><U+0646><U+0634><U+064A><U+0629> <U+0628><U+0627><U+0644><U+0625><U+0633><U+0643><U+0646><U+062F><U+0631><U+064A><U+0629>|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram (Arabic)}}</ref> The situation was alarming though to political activists who organized the demonstrations in the few days prior to the revolution due to the violent clashes that erupted between opponents and supporters of Morsi resulting in a number of deaths including an American student. The city hasn't seen the kind of clashes it had witnessed in the previous days but the FJP however accused anti-Morsi protesters of rioting and of being behind the ransacking of their party's office in the [[Hadara|El-Hadara]] district earlier on Sunday.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/>

Nearly every [[Governorates of Egypt|governorate]] saw its own demonstrations with huge ones taking place in several cities all over Egypt, including [[Mansoura]], [[Damanhour]], [[Mahalla]], [[Suez]], [[Port Said]] and [[Minya, Egypt|Minya]]. In the [[Nile Delta]]'s [[Menoufia]], hundreds staged anti-Morsi protests in the city of [[Ashmoun]]. Some in other parts of the governorate have cut off the [[Cairo<U+2013>Alexandria desert road#Cairo<U+2013>Alexandria agricultural road|Cairo-Alexandria agricultural road]] while others have closed off seven city council buildings, among them [[Menouf]]'s, with chains and signs reading "Closed by order of the people".<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref name="Egypt Independent Delta">{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/protests-raging-across-egypt-governorates|title=Protests raging across Egypt governorates|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref><ref name="Al-Ahram Weekly June 30"/> [[Sharqia]], where Morsi had lost before to his rival candidate [[Ahmed Shafik]] by about 160,000 votes in the [[Egyptian presidential election, 2012|2012 election]], had thousands demonstrating across the province with the capital [[Zagazig]] hosting several protests concentrated around the governorate building and in Orabi Square.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/> The FJP office was attacked by armed assailants just hours after an ''Al-Ahram'' interview with the local party leader Ahmed Shehata when he presented his own version of Sunday's protests claiming that the number of "real revolutionaries" protesting peacefully that day would not exceed 20,000 across Egypt. The attack claimed the life of 21 year-old student Hossam Shoqqi, who had previously served tea for the reporters. Zagazig overall had a strong anti-Morsi sentiment already and was prominent with graffiti and posters slamming the Muslim Brotherhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/152/75267/Egypt/Morsi,-one-year-on/Morsis-hometown-divided-on-day-of-mass-protests.aspx|title=Morsi's hometown divided on day of mass protests|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> [[Gharbia]] saw tens of thousands of demonstrators in the capital [[Tanta]]. Several marches have been delayed till afternoon prayers in the industrial city of Mahalla, known for its strong revolutionary spirit.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/01/violence-mars-nationwide-marches/|title=Sporadic clashes at nationwide marches|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> But the city witnessed major protests and the numbers have dramatically increased afterwards, with workers forming the majority of the protesters. Reportedly 90% of workers at the state-owned [[Misr Spinning and Weaving Company]], the country's largest factory employing over 25,000 workers, went on strike to join the protests, and along with other textile workers across the city, have previously warned several times that under Morsi their factories are threatened with closure altogether.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2013/07/01/egyp-j01.html|title=Mass protests erupt against US-backed Mursi regime in Egypt|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=World Socialist Web Site}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juancole.com/2013/07/demonstrations-egyptian-president.html|title=Biggest Demonstrations in Egyptian History: Millions Demand President Morsi Step Down|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Informed Comment}}</ref> The protesters chanted slogans like "[[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Abdel Nasser]] said it before, the Muslim Brotherhood are not to be trusted".<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/> Prominent labour activist [[Kamal el-Fayoumi]] told ''Al-Ahram'' that "Mahalla contributed heavily to the removal of Mubarak from power, and we will do the same thing with Morsi".<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/> Hundreds participated in demonstrations in [[Kafr El Zayat]] against Morsi with anti-Muslim Brotherhood chants such as "National unity against the Brotherhood" and "You who rule in the name of religion, where is justice and where is religion?"<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/> The [[Dakahlia Governorate]] city of Mansoura saw hundreds of thousands continuously flocking in the city's main Al-Shaheed Square from several rally points. Chants included "Go, you're two-faced, you've divided the people in two" and the protests had notable persons participating such as [[Mohamed Ghonim]], a leading Middle East [[urologist]], in a different mass march in the city.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/01/protesters-across-the-nation-respond-to-tamarods-calls/|title=Protesters across the nation respond to Tamarod<U+2019>s calls|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> Similarly to the events in Sharqia and Gharbia, the city of [[Desouk]] in [[Kafr el-Sheikh]] had demonstrators closing the city council building and the governorate complex which consists of several governmental institutions including the Media Centre, Tax Authority and cotton ginning companies. The protesters said the buildings will be locked down until the regime is ousted and when local departments are formed to run provincial authorities following consultations with political groups in the city.<ref name="Egypt Independent Delta"/> This kind of action also managed to take place in [[Beheira]], with protesters shutting down the local councils in [[Mahmoudiyah, Egypt|Mahmoudiya]] and [[Itay al-Baroud]], as well as other municipalities in the governorate's capital Damanhour before erecting tents outside all of the besieged buildings. Thousands demonstrated in Damanhour's main square, where some carried police officers on their shoulders chanting against the government, and marches in the city attracted around 30,000 protesters, along with 10,000 in [[Kafr el-Dawwar]] and 5,000 in [[Kom Hamada]].<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref name="Egypt Independent Delta"/><ref name="Al-Ahram Weekly June 30"/> The port city of [[Damietta]] in the north was estimated to have several thousand demonstrators in the streets, according to a member of the [[Socialist Popular Alliance Party|Socialist Popular Alliance]], with some in Al-Saa'a Square demanding early presidential elections. Around 250 fishing boats sailed in the [[Nile]] heading to the square using megaphones to chant anti-Mori slogans. They have taken over the governorate headquarters and the offices of the local educational authority and also planned to occupy other government buildings to prevent governor Tarek Khedr from entering his office.<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/><ref name="Egypt Independent Delta"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/250-fishing-boats-sail-damietta-protest-morsy|title=250 fishing boats sail in Damietta, protest Morsy|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref>

A similar scene took place in the [[Upper Egypt]]ian [[Luxor Governorate|governorate]] of [[Luxor]], where a flotilla consisting of boats and [[Launch (boat)|motor launches]] packed with people in hundreds waving Egyptian flags and chanting "Leave Morsi!" accompanied by drums, reportedly sailed down the Nile voicing their opposition to the president. Both river banks saw a huge number of protesters in a city that rarely witnesses unrest, with masses demonstrating across Luxor en route to one of their rallying points at the governorate building, where a sit-in was planned until their demands are met. There was a line of men on the corniche holding hands and making a corridor packed with women of all ages into the front, sealing off area of the governor<U+2019>s office. [[Luxor Temple]] was the site another gathering, where marches from [[Karnak]], Sawagi and Awamea had met and the temple's exterior became full in the afternoon despite the stifling heat that day.<ref name="TribLIVE">{{cite web|url=http://triblive.com/usworld/betsyhiel/4286334-74/morsy-egypt-brotherhood#axzz2tQDbRwqZ|title=Protesters overrun Egypt streets|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=TribLIVE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://marahouseluxor.com/luxor-miracle-30-june-2013-morsi-leave/|title=Luxor <U+2013> the Miracle of 30 June 2013 <U+2013> "Morsi LEAVE!"|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Mara House Luxor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://arabia.msn.com/news/middle-east/1949740/live-updates-2-millions-on-streets-for-anti-morsi-protests-4-dead-in-upper-egypt/|title=Live updates 2: Millions on streets for anti-Morsi protests; 4 dead in Upper Egypt|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=MSN News}}</ref> 3,500 anti-Morsi demonstrators were reported in the city of [[Aswan]] south of the Luxor and [[Qena Governorate|Qena]] governorates. There were escalating verbal confrontations between opponents and supporters of Morsi in Aswan's main Shohadah Square as lawyers had gathered for a march heading to the square from the city court.<ref name="Aswat Masriya updates"/><ref name="TribLIVE"/> Tamarod, joined by a number of parties such as the [[New Wafd Party|Wafd Party]], announced an open ended sit-in in [[Sohag Governorate|Sohag]], where tens of thousands closed the governorate office with chains, setting up protest tents and blocking state employees from entering the building.<ref name="Al-Ahram Weekly June 30"/> In the provincial capital's Culture Square, the city's largest, revolutionary forces have announced their intention to march after mid-day prayers. Shops were closed and the city's trading activity was relatively calm. The protesters chanted against the Brotherhood and called for national unity between Muslims and Christians while other marches were arriving from all over Sohag and from surrounding villages. On the other hand, hundreds of Islamists and their supporters gathered in front of the city's Korman mosque in support of Morsi. A near confrontation would inevitable between pro and anti-Morsi demonstrators if the police had not intervened forcing the Islamists to abandon the site for Tamarod.<ref name="Aswat Masriya updates"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawadeth.akhbarelyom.com/news/newdetails/141020/0/0.html#.UwDVZYWp2sY|title=<U+0645><U+0638><U+0627><U+0647><U+0631><U+0627><U+062A> 30 <U+064A><U+0648><U+0646><U+064A><U+0648> <U+0628><U+0633><U+0648><U+0647><U+0627><U+062C> <U+0628><U+062F><U+0623><U+062A> <U+0645><U+0646> <U+0627><U+0644><U+062B><U+0642><U+0627><U+0641><U+0629> <U+0648><U+0645><U+0631><U+0627><U+0643><U+0632> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0645><U+062D><U+0627><U+0641><U+0638><U+0629>|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Hawadeth (Arabic)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tahrirnews.com/news/view.aspx?cdate=30062013&id=130aebc0-c745-4b21-8600-49c4afa5161e|title=<U+0645><U+0638><U+0627><U+0647><U+0631><U+0627><U+062A> <U+0633><U+0648><U+0647><U+0627><U+062C> <U+062A><U+0647><U+062A><U+0641> "<U+0645><U+0633><U+0644><U+0645> <U+0645><U+0633><U+064A><U+062D><U+0649> <U+0627><U+064A><U+062F> <U+0648><U+0627><U+062D><U+062F><U+0647>"|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Tahrir (Arabic)}}</ref> [[Tahta]], another city in the [[Sohag Governorate]], witnessed thousands in its main streets demanding the ouster of President Mohamed Morsi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gate.ahram.org.eg/News/366266.aspx|title=<U+0645><U+0633><U+064A><U+0631><U+0627><U+062A> <U+062D><U+0627><U+0634><U+062F><U+0629> <U+062A><U+062C><U+0648><U+0628> <U+0634><U+0648><U+0627><U+0631><U+0639> <U+0637><U+0647><U+0637><U+0627> <U+0648><U+062A><U+0637><U+0627><U+0644><U+0628> <U+0628><U+0631><U+062D><U+064A><U+0644> <U+0645><U+0631><U+0633><U+0649>|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram (Arabic)}}</ref> The [[Asyut Governorate|governorate of Assiut]], an Islamist stronghold which was the site of this day's deadliest clashes, a [[Drive-by shooting|drive-by]] took place in the capital [[Assiut]] where it was estimated that more than 50,000 were protesting in the city by night. Gunmen on a motorcycle opened fire on a protest in which tens of thousands were participating, killing one person and wounding four, sending the panicked crowd running. The enraged protesters later marched on the nearby FJP offices, where gunmen inside the compound shot at them, killing two more demonstrators, according to security officials who were speaking on condition of anonymity because they weren't authorized to talk to the press. The clashes later escalated with protesters fighting alongside security forces on one side and Morsi's supporters on the other.<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/egypts.christians.praying.for.end.to.bloodshed.and.violence/33021.htm|title=Egypt's Christians praying for end to bloodshed and violence|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Christian Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/egypt-protesters-gather-demand-morsis-ouster|title=Egypt erupts with protests demanding Morsi ouster|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Associated Press}}</ref> Another deadly confrontation occurred in [[Beni Suef]] where opponents of Mohamed Morsi torched the ruling FJP's offices earlier in the morning, hours before mass protests were about to take place in the province. Nasser Saad, the FJP's media spokesman in Beni Suef, said that several protesters threw [[Molotov cocktails]] at the building's balconies around two o'clock in the morning before moving to a secretariat office and torched it too.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/75298.aspx|title=FJP offices torched in Beni Suef, thousands out in governorates for 30 June|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> Later that day, one protester was killed and 30 were injured, according to Beni Suef's security chief, when unknown assailants fired at anti-Morsi protests in El-Modereya Square. Following the shooting, Al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya claimed in a statement that the person killed was a member of the Islamist group while the office of Hamdeen Sabahi's [[Egyptian Popular Current|Popular Current]] claimed that members of the "jihadist movement" in the city was the one behind the attack. The health ministry confirmed however that 25 year-old Ammar Gouda was the protester who died while participating in anti-Morsi protests. The army arrived to break up the situation and the demonstrations quietly continued later on.<ref name="Al Ahram June 30 Live 2"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/75362/Egypt/Politics-/Egypts-AlGamaa-AlIslamiya-claims-slain-Beni-Suef-m.aspx|title=Egypt's Al-Gamaa Al-Islamiya claims slain Beni Suef man as its own|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/75347/Egypt/Politics-/One-dead,--injured-in-attack-on-antiMorsi-rally-in.aspx|title=One dead, 30 injured in attack on anti-Morsi rally in Beni Suef|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> In [[Minya]], around a hundred protesters gathered at Palace Square, chanting against Morsi and the Brotherhood while around five hundred lawyers, who started a march from the court's complex in Minya, also chanted against the regime. Muslim Brotherhood youth formed popular committees to protect the FJP headquarters.<ref name="Aswat Masriya updates"/> There were other violent clashes in the [[Faiyum Governorate]] in which hundreds of Morsi opponents clashed with his Islamist supporters outside the Muslim Brotherhood's local FJP office. Both sides were pelting sticks and stones at each other in the Al-Masala district and there were also unconfirmed reports of rubber bullets being used mutually by the clashing demonstrators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.aswatmasriya.com/news/view.aspx?id=8d4f5844-2496-4c87-b5f0-a7f11642f03a|title=Hundreds clash outside FJP headquarters in Fayoum|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Aswat Masriya}}</ref>

====Storming of the Muslim Brotherhood headquarters====
Around midnight, the Muslim Brotherhood's national headquarters in Cairo's [[Mokattam]] district, whom Morsi's critics view as the government's real seat of power in the country, came under attack when anti-Morsi protesters started throwing Molotov cocktails and rocks at the six-story building's windows. There were also reports of shotguns being used from the side of the protesters according to the Brotherhood's spokesman [[Gehad El-Haddad]] who said that the attackers had been successfully repelled by the officials present in the building.<ref name="Yahoo MB HQ">{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/egypt-protesters-storm-muslim-brotherhood-hq-095733433.html|title=Egypt: Protesters storm Muslim Brotherhood HQ|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Yahoo News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/news/cairo-protesters-brotherhood-hq-454/|title=Shotguns, petrol bombs and rocks: Scores of protesters storm Muslim Brotherhood HQ in Cairo|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=RT}}</ref> This however proved untrue as clashes immediately followed the all-night siege with [[birdshot]] and live ammunition reportedly exchanged between the two sides.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/muslim-brotherhood-hq-stormed-qalyubiya|title=Muslim Brotherhood HQ stormed in Qalyubiya|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref> According to the Health Ministry, eight people have been killed as the rioting continued until next morning when anti-Morsi protesters eventually stormed the compound, despite being barricaded with sandbags prior to the attack, and the building was later ransacked and torched.<ref name="BBC Crisis July 1"/><ref name="BBC MB HQ"/> Looting took place the next morning with rioters carting off furniture, blankets, rugs, files and air-conditioning devices among others. Fire was reportedly still raging from one floor as protesters tore down the Muslim Brotherhood signs from the building's front facade and another waved the Egyptian flag from an upper-story window.<ref name="Yahoo MB HQ"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/01/egypt-muslim-brotherhood-offices-civil|title=Egypt faces more bloodshed as Muslim Brotherhood offices torched|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>

===July 1===
As the protests headed into their second day, the plundering persisted at the Brotherhood's headquarters compound, the site of fierce clashes the previous night.<ref name="Yahoo MB HQ"/> The protesters were already gearing up for new rallies this day, with some having spent the night in several tents that were installed in Tahrir Square and around Ittihadiya Palace. Protesters in Tahrir staged a sit-in around the [[The Mogamma|Mogamma building]] and completely surrounded the government complex early in the morning, demanding the departure of President Mohamed Morsi and early presidential elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/01/protesters-shut-down-mogamma-launch-civil-disobedience-movement/|title=Protesters shut down Mogamma, launch civil disobedience movement|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> Around 600 families who were affiliated with the so-called "[[Couch Party]]" staged demonstrations in the up-scale [[Greater Cairo]] district of [[Mohandessin]], along with others in the [[El-Manial]] district in southern Cairo, calling for Morsi to resign and some brought sofas with them as a way of displaying how unashamed they are of belonging to this movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/egypt-s-couch-party-takes-streets|title=Egypt's "couch party" takes to the streets|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref> In the evening, the band [[Cairokee]] performed for thousands of protesters in front of the presidential palace after receiving an invitation by volunteer organizers. They later thanked all the protesters who sang along with them during their performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/variety/2013/07/02/Drowning-out-the-anger-Egypt-s-Cairokee-turns-protest-into-rock-fest-.html|title=Drowning out the anger, Egypt<U+2019>s <U+2018>Cairokee<U+2019> turns protest into rock fest|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=A-Arabiya}}</ref> There have been calls by organizers for sit-ins at the Cabinet building, interim parliament, and another presidential place by the demonstrations' organizers, as well as other calls for nationwide labor strikes to pressure the government but there were no reported responses by the country's [[Trade unions in Egypt|trade unions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2013/07/egypt-protests-claim-several-lives-as-protesters-flood-streets-of-cairo-90806.html|title=Egypt protests claim several lives as protesters flood streets of Cairo|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=ABC News - WJLA}}</ref> Tamarod released a statement giving Morsi a deadline to step down until the next day at 5:00 PM, warning him they would hike up the demonstrations marching on all palaces and that he would face a mass campaign of "complete civil disobedience". They also requested a new presidential election as part of their declaration and called on the military and police to make it clear that they support the protesters.<ref name="Tamarod deadline">{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/egypts-protesters-morsi-deadline-134428624.html|title= Egypt's protesters give Morsi deadline to go|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Yahoo News}}</ref> In addition, five [[Qandil Cabinet|cabinet ministers]] resigned in solidarity with the protests. They were Minister of Communication and IT [[Atef Helmy]], Minister of Environment [[Khaled Abdel-Aal]], Minister of Water Utilities [[Abdel Qawi Khalifa]], Minister of Legal and Parliamentary Affairs [[Hatem Bagato]], who had previously stated on Sunday that the [[Supreme Constitutional Court of Egypt|Supreme Constitutional Court]] (SCC) cannot dismiss the president from office, and finally Minister of Tourism [[Hisham Zazou]], who had previously submitted his resignation to PM Hesham Qandil earlier in June after Morsi appointed as governor of Luxor an ex-militant linked to a group that was responsible for the [[Luxor massacre|massacre of tourists]] in 1997, but later came back to office when the governor resigned instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/01/ministers-resign-in-protest-of-latest-clashes/|title=Ministers resign in protest of latest clashes|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201307020417.html|title=Egypt: Five Ministers Resign After Mass Protests|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=allAfrica}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|See <ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jun/19/egypt-tourism-minister-resigns-luxor-hisham-zaazou|title=Egypt tourism minister resigns over Luxor governor's terror links|date=June 19, 2013|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/06/24/tourism-minister-back-in-office-as-luxor-sit-in-continues/|title=Tourism minister back in office as Luxor sit-in continues|date=June 24, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref>}} Also, eight independent parliamentarians from the Islamist-dominated [[Shura Council]] officially resigned from the body in protest and solidarity with the opposition's demands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/75419/Egypt/Politics-/-Shura-Council-members-resign-in-protest-at-politi.aspx|title=8 Shura Council members resign in protest at political standoff|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref>

Like many scenarios that occurred in the Delta on Sunday, Upper Egypt also had demonstrators occupying government buildings, most notably in Assiut and Sohag. Dozens barricaded the governorate office in Sohag with chains, setting up protest tents and blocking state employees from entering the building and the police intervened to separate protesters from pro-Brotherhood employees following the closure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/protesters-force-governorate-offices-close-across-egypt|title=Protesters force governorate offices to close across Egypt|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref> In Assiut, thousands attended the funerals of the three protesters who were killed on Sunday during evening clashes chanting against the Brotherhood. The body of Mohamed Abdel Hamid, a director at the [[National Bank of Egypt|National Bank]], was carried by hundreds of activists who were marching in front of the governorate building where the confrontation took place the night before, waving national flags and calling for retribution and then headed to the cemetery where he was buried. Simultaneously, residents in three villages held the funeral of the second victim, Mohamed Nasef, who belonged to one of the biggest families in Assiut. The grieving was marked by family anger with chanting of slogans, and was held amid extreme security measures. Abanoub Atef, the third victim, had his service taking place in the Church of the Resurrection, amid anger and resentment, and was attended by a number of activists.The local Wafd Party held the Brotherhood and the Islamist group al-Gamaa al-Islamiya responsible for the deaths and injuries and accused them of encouraging their supporters to attack unarmed civilians under the guise of "[[jihad]]" for God.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201307020571.html|title=Egypt: Thousands Mourn Assiut Deaths, Chanting Against Mursi|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=allAfrica}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/funerals-held-victims-30-june-clashes-assiut|title=Funerals held for victims of 30 June clashes in Assiut|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/01/assiut-mourns-its-dead/|title=Assiut mourns its dead|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> Supporters and opponents of Mohamed Morsi exchanged gunfire in Suez as the sound of shots rocked the city, while the governor of Ismailia, Hassan el-Rifaai, resigned from office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/07/01/us-egypt-protests-suez-idUSBRE96018S20130701|title=Rival Egypt protesters exchange gunfire in Suez: witnesses|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/egypt-heads-2nd-day-anti-president-protest|title=Egypt's military issues 48-hour ultimatum|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Associated Press}}</ref>

{{Rquote|left|The Armed Forces renews its call and give the political forces a 48 hour ultimatum as a last chance to carry the burdens of this historic situation that the nation is going through.

The Armed Forces calls upon everyone that if the people's demands aren't set within the timeframe, based on its historic and national obligation it will have to declare a roadmap and procedures that oversee to include all mainstreams including the youth who started this glorious revolution without excluding anyone<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2013/07/01/heres-the-egyptian-militarys-full-statement-warning-it-may-act-in-48-hours/|title=Here<U+2019>s the Egyptian military<U+2019>s full statement warning it may act in 48 hours|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref>|Gen. [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]], Minister of Defense}}

====Military ultimatum====
The army issued a statement on live television in response to the huge protest marches and violent clashes that have swept Cairo and other cities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/egypt/10152780/Egypt-protests-Army-issues-48-hour-ultimatum-for-agreement-amid-clashes.html|title=Egypt protests: Army issues 48-hour ultimatum for agreement amid clashes|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> General [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]] said that the country's "political forces" involved in the crisis have 48 hours to meet the people's demands or else the armed forces would intervene to impose a road map. An hour later, five military helicopters trailing with huge national flags flew in broad circles over Cairo as thousands of demonstrators in Tahrir Square and in the vicinity of the presidential palace applauded them. In celebration of the announcement, millions of Egyptians started re-flooding the streets, where thousands still remained from Sunday's mass protests against Morsi. The crowds appeared to believe that this was the end for Morsi and according to some, the timing of the military declaration, coming only 24 hours before the next round of opposition protests, seemed certain to encourage the president<U+2019>s opponents. A Morsi aide told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that el-Sisi's ultimatum was "a military coup". But the army denied it insisted that it was seeking to stop Egypt from entering a "dark tunnel of conflict". The National Salvation Front also endorsed the ultimatum and supported the military's decision as a defense of the will of the people. Finally, late in the day the Muslim Brotherhood said the army action was not a coup but a security measure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/middle-east-live/2013/jul/01/egypt-stanoff-millions-protest|title=Egypt protests: army issues 48-hour ultimatum - as it happened|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/07/egyptian-military-threatens-intervention-following-protests.html|title=Egypt<U+2019>s Military Steps In, Issues Ultimatum|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Al-Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/07/01/egyptians-react-to-armys-ultimatum/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|title=Egyptians React to Army<U+2019>s Ultimatum|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>

===July 2===
In Cairo, demonstrators were pouring into Tahrir Square, where popular committees were blocking all roads leading in and out of the already packed square after two major marches arrived from Shubra and Mohandessin.<ref name="LU Ahram July 2">{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/75511.aspx|title=Live updates: Millions on streets in Egypt as defiant Morsi addresses nation|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref><ref name="allAfrica June 2">{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201307021122.html|title=Egypt: Anti-Mursi Demonstrations Resume in Tahrir and Ittihadiya|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=allAfrica}}</ref> An artists' rally, smaller in size than the one from Sunday but still counting several hundreds, marched to Tahrir through Qasr al-Nil Bridge after gathering once again in front of the culture ministry. They were led by some professional vocalists into singing the Egyptian national anthem along with chants such as "Egypt is a secular country" and "Revolution continues".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/5/35/75529/Arts--Culture/Stage--Street/Egypt-artists-stage-second-antiMorsi-march-to-Tahr.aspx|title=Egypt artists stage second anti-Morsi march to Tahrir Square|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> Mass rallies of thousands in Ittihadiya Palace<U+2019>s surroundings were peaceful and were jubilant as well, with men and women dancing to patriotic music. ''Al-Ahram'' reported that the numbers were bigger than Monday with an increase of tents in al-Merghany Street by the palace. There were also volunteer-manned checkpoints that have been tightened up since the day before, searching car trunks and women<U+2019>s purses.<ref name="LU Ahram July 2"/><ref name="allAfrica June 2"/> Tens of thousands have gathered at the [[Koubbeh Palace|Qubba presidential palace]] and the numbers kept increasing till the end of the day. Fireworks are lighting up the sky. At a nearby underground metro station, crowds were so large that the station workers have opened the metro barriers to allow people to exit easily. Groups of people wearing high-visibility jackets were spreading out patrolling the demonstration. Qubba<U+2019>s vicinity, one of this day<U+2019>s highlights, became a major location for protests only this weekend because [[2012<U+2013>13 Egyptian protests|during the previous months]] anti-Morsi marches usually headed to Tahrir Square or to Ittihadiya instead. The reason behind that is because the president moved from the Egypt<U+2019>s official presidential palace to Quba Palace, and as a result, the site became a popular rallying point for demonstrations during this uprising.<ref name="LU Ahram July 2"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elwatannews.com/news/details/217037|title=<U+0645><U+0633><U+064A><U+0631><U+0627><U+062A> "<U+0627><U+0644><U+0632><U+0627><U+0648><U+064A><U+0629> <U+0627><U+0644><U+062D><U+0645><U+0631><U+0627><U+0621>" <U+0648>"<U+0627><U+0644><U+062A><U+062D><U+0631><U+064A><U+0631>" <U+062A><U+062A><U+0648><U+0627><U+0641><U+062F> <U+0639><U+0644><U+0649> <U+0642><U+0635><U+0631> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0642><U+0628><U+0629>|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Al-Watan (Arabic)}}</ref> Many protesters were chanting in favour of the military and Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, as chants of "the people and the army are one hand" were very common and spray-painted <U+201C>Game Over<U+201D> on the gates of the palace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/02/protests-continue-at-presidential-al-qobba-palaces-and-tahrir-square/|title=Protests continue at presidential, Al-Qobba palaces and Tahrir Square|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> Another wave of resignations similar to Monday's included Foreign Minister [[Mohamed Kamel Amr]] who decided to step down in response to the unrest, along with presidential spokesman Ehab Fahmy and cabinet spokesman Alaa al-Hadidi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/75458/Egypt/Politics-/Egypts-foreign-minister-resigns-following-antiMors.aspx|title=Egypt's foreign minister resigns following anti-Morsi rallies|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/latest-wave-resignations-cabinet-presidency-spokesmen-quit|title=Latest wave of resignations as Cabinet, Presidency spokesmen quit|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref>

This day saw significant numbers of pro-Morsi marches across the country as many started to suspect a coup would take place. Hundreds of Morsi supporters gathered in front of [[Cairo University]] in Al-Nahda Square as nationwide demonstrations entered their third consecutive day. The protesters, whose numbers were increasing, blocked roads leading to the front gates of the campus and erected a stage in a show of support for the embattled president<U+2019>s legitimacy following a statement issued by the armed forces on Monday. The rallies, along with many other similar ones in several parts of Egypt, were organized by Salafist groups such as Al-Gamaa al-Islamiyya which stated that pro-Morsi demonstrations this day would take place in 11 different governorates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/02/cairo-university-demonstration-fears-armed-forces-return-to-politics/|title=Cairo University demonstration fears Armed Forces<U+2019> return to politics|date=June 2, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/02/al-jamaa-al-islamiya-organises-nationwide-demonstrations/|title=Al-Jamaa Al-Islamiya organises nationwide demonstrations|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> Around Rabaa Al-Adawiya Mosque in Nasr City, the president<U+2019>s supporters gathered in their hundreds of thousands, a clear defiance of the millions of anti-Morsi demonstrators who gathered in dozens of squares across Egypt.<ref name="LU Ahram July 2"/> In Upper Egypt, thousands of Morsi supporters prominently gathered in the cities of Minya, Assiut and Qena among others. In front of Minya<U+2019>s Al-Rahman mosque which is known in the city as an Al-Gamaa Al-Islamiya spot, thousands gathered in a march towards the city<U+2019>s Palace Square where hundreds of anti-Morsi protesters had been staging a sit-in against the recently-appointed Islamist affiliated governor. According to Al-Ahram, a number of people from the pro-Morsi rally reportedly fired at protesters in front of the governorate building which resulted in a violent confrontation.<ref name="LU Ahram July 2"/><ref name="Pro-Morsi Dem Ahram">{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/75448/Egypt/Politics-/ProMorsi-marches-reported-in-Cairo,-governorates;-.aspx|title=Pro-Morsi marches reported in Cairo, governorates; rival marchers clash in Suez|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> Thousands of Morsi's supporters took to the streets in Sa<U+2019>a Square in Qena in a rally organized by the ruling Freedom and Justice Party, along with their ultra-conservative allies, Al-Gamaa Al-Islamiya, the [[Raya Party]] and the [[Al-Watan Party (Egypt)|Watan Party]].<ref name="LU Ahram July 2"/><ref name="Pro-Morsi Dem Ahram"/> Assiut<U+2019>s Omar Makram Mosque vicinity also saw thousands gathering in support of what they called <U+201C>the present<U+2019>s legitimacy<U+201D>. At the same time however, hundreds of Morsi<U+2019>s opponents gathered in a demonstration in front of the city<U+2019>s governorate headquarters.<ref name="LU Ahram July 2"/> Thousands of pro-Morsi demonstrators took over Sohag<U+2019>s Culture Square pushing anti-Morsi protesters to retreat into other streets of the city in fear of clashes.<ref name="LU Ahram July 2"/> Protests have also took place in the northern city of [[Marsa Matruh]].<ref name="Pro-Morsi Dem Ahram"/>

There were deadly clashes across the country, as the Cairo University demonstration in [[Giza]]'s Al-Nahda Square witnessed a violent confrontation between pro and anti-Morsi demonstrators in the surrounding streets. [[Human Rights Watch]] reported that the clashes left 18 killed, 4 of whom were confirmed residents, and scores injured when, according to Muslim Brotherhood supporters, armed "thugs" attacked their sit-in as an exchange of automatic gunfire intensified after 10:00 PM. Residents acknowledged they armed themselves with rocks and knives, while Morsi's supporters acknowledged to have carried guns during the riot in the intersection of the campus' main road and Ahmed Zewail Street.<ref name="HRW Cairo University">{{cite web|url=http://www.hrw.org/news/2013/07/05/egypt-deadly-clashes-cairo-university|title=Egypt: Deadly Clashes at Cairo University|date=July 5, 2013|publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> Security forces intervened as a goal of restoring order but ended up clashing with Morsi supporters instead and teargas was used.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/07/02/us-egypt-protests-university-idUSBRE9611AO20130702|title=Police, Mursi supporters clash in Cairo, many hurt|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> There was conflict in another parts of Giza earlier that day, such as in Faisal Street where seven were wounded after their march was shot at from the side of Morsi's supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/brotherhood-demonstrators-shoot-morsy-opponents|title=Brotherhood demonstrators shoot at Morsy opponents|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref> In the [[Imbaba]] district, gunfire was exchanged during clashes in Kit Kat Square using pellets and Molotov cocktails. There was one death confirmed by the health ministry and the injured were taken to hospitals in Imbaba and [[Agouza]] leaving the site of confrontation with rocks and glass scattered all over.<ref name="LU Ahram July 2"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/07/02/latest-updates-on-egypts-political-crisis/|title=July 2 Updates on Egypt<U+2019>s Political Crisis|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> Other parts of Egypt also saw violent clashes such as [[Agami]] in the governorate of Alexandria, where the police tried to contain the scuffles between pro and anti-Morsi protesters by firing teargas with the head of Alexandria's investigative department reporting 25 injured. In [[Qalyubia Governorate|Qalyubia]]'s city of [[Banha]], the Brotherhood<U+2019>s FJP local headquarters was torched after it was stormed by anti-Morsi protesters. The building was ransacked and the banner that carries the name of the party was removed. Other clashes were confirmed in the [[Beheira Governorate|Beheira]] and [[Luxor Governorate|Luxor]] governorates.<ref name="LU Ahram July 2"/>

====Morsi's speech====
Later that night, President Mohamed Morsi made his first official speech since the events began on Sunday where he appeared defiant to the military's ultimatum and refused to back down. He admitted that me made mistakes but insisted that he was the legitimate democratically elected president and hinted that any effort to remove him by force would plunge the nation into chaos. He also seemed to disregard the record numbers of Egyptians who took to the streets demanding his resignation:<ref name="NYC Morsi speech">{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/03/world/middleeast/egypt-protests.html?pagewanted=all|title=Morsi Defies Egypt Army<U+2019>s Ultimatum to Bend to Protest|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/egypts-morsi-says-he-wont-step-down-vows-protect-his-v19246354|title=Egypt's Morsi says he won't step down, vows to protect his legitimacy|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=NBC News}}</ref>
<blockquote>"The people empowered me, the people chose me, through a free and fair election,

Legitimacy is the only way to protect our country and prevent bloodshed, to move to a new phase,... Legitimacy is the only thing that guarantees for all of us that there will not be any fighting and conflict, that there will not be bloodshed.

If the price of protecting legitimacy is my blood, I<U+2019>m willing to pay it,... And it would be a cheap price for the sake of protecting this country."<ref name="NYC Morsi speech"/></blockquote>
The speech was immediately denounced by opposition activists who viewed it as delusional and made them feel instead that their battle was largely won. On the other hand, thousands of Morsi<U+2019>s supporters kept demonstrating across the country and chanting their slogan "Legitimacy", a word that repeated by Morsi at least two dozen times in the speech, to counter their opponents<U+2019> "Leave". Some Muslim Brotherhood members said that if a coup did happen, they would await orders from the group's leaders. Many remained convinced, however, that the military would stand back and change its mind to avoid bloodshed and violence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/egypts-morsi-under-increasing-pressure-as-deadline-looms/2013/07/02/fcb11aa0-e315-11e2-a11e-c2ea876a8f30_story.html|title=Egypt<U+2019>s Morsi defiant under pressure as deadline looms|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref>

===July 3: Reaching deadline===
{{Expand section|date=February 2014}}
Before the deadline passed, Tahrir Square was still filling up with anti-Morsi demonstrators with the central square partially full while surrounding streets were still relatively empty.<ref name="LU Al-Ahram July 3">{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/75594.aspx|title=Live updates: Morsi ousted; head of constitutional court to take over Egypt presidency|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> It started to crowd however, and when the 48-hour period ended, Tahrir was completely packed with hundreds of thousands of protesters who were awaiting a statement by military chief el-Sisi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-23170441|title=Egypt protests: Tahrir Square 'absolutely packed'|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref name="Egypt Independent Tahrir July 3">{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/hundreds-thousands-flock-tahrir-hear-army-statement|title=Hundreds of thousands flock to Tahrir to hear army statement|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref> Protesters closed the gates of Tahrir's iconic Mogamma building in the southern part of the square for the second time since Monday, two days before, but reopened it on Tuesday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/tahrir-protesters-close-mugamma|title=Tahrir protesters close Mugamma|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent}}</ref> Hundreds of demonstrators carried a coffin representing President Mohamed Morsi in a symbolic funeral which roamed around Tahrir Square as three lambs were slaughtered representing Mohamed Morsi, Muslim Brotherhood Supreme Guide [[Mohamed Badie]] and Brotherhood deputy leader [[Khairat el-Shater]], referring to "sheep", a [[derogatory term]] popular among Brotherhood opponents used to describe followers of the group in Egypt.<ref name="Egypt Independent Tahrir July 3"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContentP/4/61597/Opinion/Cairo-the-city-vanquished-The-Muslim-Brotherhood-a.aspx|title=Cairo: the city vanquished? The Muslim Brotherhood and the ruralisation of Egypt|date=December 31, 2012|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref> The atmosphere was generally celebratory as the thousands of demonstrators were waving national flags and chanting against Morsi. Hundreds of women holding hands were chanting "Morsi, get out!", while they were encircled by a human shield that was viewed as necessary to curb the number of sexual assaults that were reported in Tahrir and its surroundings since the uprising began on June 30. Anti-sexual violence groups such as [[Tahrir Bodyguard]] and [[Operation Anti Sexual Harassment]] wore recognizable neon yellow vests and helmets and were monitoring the scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/07/human-shield-protects-egyptian-women-protesters.html#|title=Egyptians Form Human Shields to Protect Female Protesters|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=Al-Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatches/globalpost-blogs/rights/hrw-sexual-attacks-women-tahrir-squarehttp://www.globalpost.com/dispatches/globalpost-blogs/rights/hrw-sexual-attacks-women-tahrir-square|title=HRW reports high numbers of sexual attacks on women in Tahrir Square|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=GlobalPost}}</ref> The vicinity of Ittihadiya Palace was almost full with people protesting against Morsi, as the band Cairokee attended the demonstrations for a second time since Monday's demonstrations in the Heliopolis suburb of Cairo and performed in front of hundreds of thousands of protesters cheering them, with lyrics such as "we are the people<U+2026> and our path is right" and "you say <U+2018>justice<U+2019>, and they call you a betrayer".<ref name="LU Al-Ahram July 3"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/03/cairokee-adds-music-to-the-chants-at-the-presidential-palace/|title=Cairokee adds music to the chants at the presidential palace|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref> Several miles away from the presidential palace, anti-Morsi demonstrators started to congregate outside the ministry of defense building and were chanting patriotically. The group of pro-military protesters was building up until the much waited announcement and they have been holding a sit-in in the location for twelve days.<ref name="LU Al-Ahram July 3"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5i0W_LYdCilHndeYztDEy_cSJOvNw?docId=CNG.fa23a9890c0f5bab3e8f2f725f5d257b.2c1&hl=en|title=Egypt protesters erupt in joy as army ousts Morsi|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=AFP}}</ref> 93 diplomats, some based in the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Egypt)|foreign affairs ministry]] declared a strike as an objection to the "failure of the president to meet the people<U+2019>s demands."<ref name="LU Al-Ahram July 3"/>

Alexandria's streets witnessed protests in masses with anti-Morsi rallies marching along its main streets, including the seafront. Several thousands kept flocking into [[Sidi Gaber]]'s station square, its surroundings and the Al Qa'ed Ibrahim Mosque in the city center, two typical rally points for anti-government demonstrations in the city.<ref name="LU Al-Ahram July 3"/> There were also tens of thousands of Morsi opponents who were stationed in the [[Sidi Bishr]] district's Mahatta Square calling for the fall of the regime. Clashes, however, took place in the neighborhood when supporters of Mohamed Morsi scuffled with the residents, leaving five injured. There were violent clashes that erupted in other parts of the city when a rally by estimated hundreds of Morsi's Islamist supporters, who were chanting "The people want to apply the law of God!", was intercepted by residents of the [[Agami]] district who tried to obstruct the march in objection to the demonstration's slogans. The confrontation left nearly seventeen injured and later required police intervention, the latter using teargas to disperse the fighting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.aswatmasriya.com/news/view.aspx?id=da0dac39-cce1-43ae-8340-53ed17368ea4|title=Update: 22 injured in Alexandria clashes|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=Aswat Masriya}}</ref> There were hundreds of thousands rallying in [[Mansoura]]'s Thawra Square, who significantly increased after el-Sisi's statement later that night. Protesters in the city continued to blockade a number of state institutions for a fourth consecutive day of their civil disobedience campaign. "The people already brought down the regime," protesters chanted, as well as "Mansoura will turn you back into a banned group".<ref name="LU Al-Ahram July 3"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/News/Details/230624|title=<U+0645><U+0626><U+0627><U+062A> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0622><U+0644><U+0627><U+0641> <U+064A><U+062D><U+062A><U+0641><U+0644><U+0648><U+0646> <U+0628><U+0640><U+00AB><U+0628><U+064A><U+0627><U+0646> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0633><U+064A><U+0633><U+064A><U+00BB> <U+0648><U+0639><U+0632><U+0644> <U+0645><U+0631><U+0633><U+064A> <U+0641><U+064A> <U+0627><U+0644><U+062F><U+0642><U+0647><U+0644><U+064A><U+0629>|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=Egypt Independent (Arabic)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://arabic.arabia.msn.com/news/egypt-news/6311642/%D8%A5%D8%BA%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82-%D9%85%D8%A8%D9%86%D9%89-%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B5%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B6%D9%8B%D8%A7-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89/|title=<U+0625><U+063A><U+0644><U+0627><U+0642> <U+0645><U+0628><U+0646><U+0649> <U+062D><U+0649> <U+0634><U+0631><U+0642> <U+0627><U+0644><U+0645><U+0646><U+0635><U+0648><U+0631><U+0629> <U+0627><U+0639><U+062A><U+0631><U+0627><U+0636><U+064B><U+0627> <U+0639><U+0644><U+0649> <U+062E><U+0637><U+0627><U+0628> <U+0645><U+0631><U+0633><U+0649>|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=MSN News (Arabic)}}</ref> [[Damietta]] saw 10,000 protesters gathering in Al-Bosta Square since Sunday.<ref name="Al-Ahram Weekly June 30"/> In different acts of [[civil disobedience]] across the country, [[Kafr el-Sheikh]] saw protesters still besieging the governorate headquarters and announced their intention to keep doing so until Morsi and his Brotherhood-appointed governor resign. In [[Tanta]], members of youth protest groups shut the gate to the Gharbiya governorate offices with metal chains, preventing employees from entering the building. In [[Menoufia]], demonstrators blocked one of the city<U+2019>s main roads. In [[Sharqia]], Morsi<U+2019>s hometown, crowds of protesters gathered outside the president<U+2019>s residence there, chanting anti-regime slogans, stating that they will start an open-ended sit-in until their demands are met, threatening to bring the whole city to a halt. [[Port Said]] witnessed protesters shutting down the Investment Authority compound.<ref name="LU Al-Ahram July 3"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/07/03/civil-disobedience-spreading/|title=Civil disobedience spreading|date=July 3, 2013|publisher=Daily News Egypt}}</ref>

==Coup d'<U+00E9>tat and aftermath==
{{main|2013 Egyptian coup d'<U+00E9>tat}}
{{Expand section|date=February 2014}}

==Solidarity with protests==
Hundreds, Egyptians and [[Australian]]s, took part in demonstrations against Mohamed Morsi in Australia's [[Melbourne]] where jubilant crowds gathered at the city<U+2019>s [[State Library of Victoria|State Library]] before marching to the Egyptian Consulate. They chanted in unity for a better future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://egyptianstreets.com/2013/06/30/egyptians-in-australia-rise-up-against-morsi/|title=Egyptians in Australia Rise Up Against Morsi|date=June 30, 2013|publisher=Egyptian Streets}}</ref>

In [[Italy]], anti-Morsi protests took place in five cities across the country: [[Milan]], [[Rome]], [[Bologna]], [[Napoli]] and [[Palermo]]. According to ''MENA'', most Egyptians in Italy joined the anti-Morsi demonstrations and that the biggest protests were located in the industrial city of Milan where two demonstrations are being held, one in [[Duomo di Milano|Duomo Square]] and the other in front of the Egyptian Consulate.<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/>

From [[South Korea]], the [[Korean Confederation of Trade Unions]] (KCTU) delivered a message of solidarity with the Egyptian workers participating in the protests, where it said:"The struggle of Egyptian people is our struggle". The statement begins with:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://menasolidaritynetwork.com/2013/07/02/egypt-korean-unions-message-to-egyptian-workers-our-struggle-is-your-struggle/|title=Egypt: Korean unions<U+2019> message to Egyptian workers "our struggle is your struggle"|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=MENA Solidarity Network}}</ref>
<blockquote>"We, the Korean Confederation of Trade Unions (KCTU) extend our warm hearted solidarity to the Egyptian Federation of Independent Trade Unions (EFITU) and all the workers and people of Egypt who took the street for bread, freedom and social justice."</blockquote>

Unjum Mirza of the [[United Kingdom|Britain]]'s [[National Union of Rail, Maritime and Transport Workers|RMT Union]] gave a speech of solidarity with the protesters in Egypt on behalf of the union in front of the Egyptian embassy in [[London]], where he was joined by many Egyptian expatriates, in which he said:<ref name="Al-Ahram June 30 Live"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://menasolidaritynetwork.com/2013/07/02/uk-message-of-solidarity-from-rmt-union-to-egypt-protests/|title=UK: Message of solidarity from RMT union to Egypt protests|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=MENA Solidarity Network}}</ref>
<blockquote>"I've decided to extend a very short message of solidarity from the Transport Union in Britain to the hundreds of thousands of millions marching across Egypt to bring down this corrupt Morsi regime"</blockquote>

==International reactions==
;Supranational bodies
* {{Flag|European Union}} - The European Union released a brief statement where it says: "We call all political forces in Egypt to remain calm, avoid violence and start a political dialogue".<ref name="Ahram Int'l reactions">{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/75439.aspx|title=International community urges calm in restive Egypt|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref>
* {{Flag|United Nations}} - UN spokesman Eduardo del Buey stated that while most of the protests appear to be peaceful, "the reports of a number of deaths and injuries, of sexual assault against women demonstrators, as well as acts of destruction of property are to be strongly condemned."<ref name="Ahram Int'l reactions"/>

;States
* {{Flag|Australia}} - While issuing a travel warning for Australians wishing to visit Egypt, Foreign Minister [[Bob Carr]] addressed the violence in Egypt. "Regrettably, there are also reports that Islamic extremists have threatened violence against Coptic churches and communities. We urge all parties to renounce violence in holding street rallies, and for the Egyptian police and military to exercise appropriate restraint in keeping public order," he said.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://foreignminister.gov.au/releases/2013/bc_mr_130701.html|title=Australians warned on Egypt travel|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (Australia)}}</ref>
* {{Flag|Canada}} - Canada has closed its embassy in Egypt amid anti-government protests in Cairo. "We're very concerned with the uncertainty that exists and that's why we closed the Canadian embassy for security reasons," Immigration Minister [[Jason Kenney]] stated on Tuesday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/07/02/canada-closes-embassy-in-egypt|title=  Canada closes embassy in Egypt |date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Toronto Sun}}</ref>
* {{Flag|France}} - French Foreign Ministry spokesman Philippe Lalliot called Egyptian authorities to listen to "the legitimate concerns" of protesters.<ref name="Ahram Int'l reactions"/>
* {{Flag|Iran}} - Iran's government on Tuesday, called on the Egyptian military to support national reconciliation and respect the "vote of the people". "Mohamed Morsi is the incumbent president based on the people's vote," Iranian deputy foreign minister Hossein Amir Abdollahian told the official [[IRNA]] news agency. "It is expected of the armed forces of Egypt that they play their role in supporting national reconciliation and respect the vote of the people".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/0/75469/Egypt/Iran-urges-Egypt-army-to-respect-vote-of-people.aspx|title=Iran urges Egypt army to respect 'vote of people'|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Al-Ahram}}</ref>
* {{Flag|Israel}} - Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] told the Italian newspaper ''[[Corriere della Sera]]'': "Like everybody, we are watching very carefully what's happening in Egypt". "Remember that for 30 years now we have had an anchor of peace and stability in the Middle East, and that was the Egyptian-Israeli peace treaty. We hope that peace will be kept".<ref name="Yahoo! Israel">{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/israel-nervously-watching-egyptian-turmoil-181757657.html|title= Israel nervously watching Egyptian turmoil|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Yahoo News}}</ref>
:Former Israeli ambassador to Egypt, Eli Shaked, said that Israel can ill afford a new crisis at a time of instability across the region. "Instability is bad for Israel. Instability is bad for the Middle East," he said. Shaked added that despite Morsi's outward hostility toward Israel, he has respected the value of maintaining ties with Israel. "Even with the extremists in power, they have shown they understand the value, or the interests of Egypt," he stated.<ref name="Yahoo! Israel"/>
* {{Flag|Nigeria}} - Foreign Affairs Minister Olugbenga Ashiru has urged the Nigerian community in Egypt to remain calm on Monday following the latest violence. "I am in touch with our ambassador in Cairo. We are watching developments carefully but there is no cause for alarm. I do believe that the authorities in Egypt will contain the situation. Also the ambassador is in contact with the leadership of the Nigerian community in Egypt on the need to remain calm," he said.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2013/07/unrest-foreign-minister-urges-nigerians-in-egypt-to-remain-calm/|title=Unrest: Foreign minister urges Nigerians in Egypt to remain calm|date=July 1, 2013|publisher=Vanguard News}}</ref>
* {{Flag|Palestinian National Authority}} - Mahmoud al-Habbash, Minister of Religious Affairs of the Palestinian Authority, urged ''[[Arab Idol]]'' star [[Mohammed Assaf]] to cancel the concerts he planned for the West Bank stating that "certain conditions and developments necessitate that we delay festivities for two or more days". He also asked national television not to broadcast anything celebratory to show sympathy and solidarity with the Egyptian people. "I am worried about Egypt, and this worry is justified both politically and in the field. I am worried because Egypt is the heart of the Arab nation, and the army of the nation," he said. However, he made it clear that this was a personal stance not an official position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maannews.net/Eng/ViewDetails.aspx?ID=610306|title=PA minister asks Assaf to cancel shows 'in solidarity with Egypt'|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Ma'an News Agency}}</ref>
* {{Flag|Russia}} - The Russian Foreign Ministry gave a statement in which it noted that all parties in Egyptian politics should refrain from using violence as it would "lead to further escalation" in the country. "We are fully aware that Egypt's contemporary issues cannot be solved unless dealt with through a legal context in order to ensure national unity and consensus on needed economic, social and political and reforms," the statement said.<ref name="Ahram Int'l reactions"/>
* {{Flag|Syria}} - Information Minister [[Omran al-Zoubi]] said that the political crisis in Egypt could only be overcome if Morsi realises that an overwhelming majority of his Egyptian people reject his presence and want him removed. On July 3, he called the Muslim Brotherhood a "terrorist" organisation and a "U.S. tool."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-202_162-57592204/syria-government-calls-for-egypts-morsi-to-step-down/ |title=Syria government calls for Egypt's Morsi to step down |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref>
* {{Flag|Tunisia}} - Tunisian Prime Minister [[Ali Laarayedh]] said in an interview on ''[[France 24]]'': "The possibility of an Egypt scenario is unlikely in Tunisia because I have great confidence in the awareness of Tunisians and their ability to measure the potential of their country".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2013/07/02/uk-tunisia-egypt-idUKBRE96102O20130702|title=Tunisia's Islamist PM says Egypt scenario unlikely to happen there|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>
* {{Flag|United Arab Emirates}} - Dubai police chief [[Dhahi Khalfan Tamim|Dhahi Khalfan]] described the statement issued by the Egyptian military as "supportive to the people's demands" on his Twitter account. "Be with people, not against them, as only they can make the country stable," he added.<ref name="Ahram Int'l reactions"/>
* {{Flag|United Kingdom}} - Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] stated in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on July 3 that: "We should appeal to all sides to stay calm and stop the levels of violence, and particularly sexual assaults", and that it is not for the United Kingdom "to support any single group or party. What we should support is proper democratic processes and proper government by consent."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expressandstar.com/news/uk-news/2013/07/03/dont-go-to-egypt-britons-warned/ |title=Cameron issues peace plea to Egypt |work=Express & Star |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref>
* {{Flag|United States}} - President [[Barack Obama]] remarked on July 1 in a press conference in Tanzania that "our number-one priority has been making sure that our embassies and consulates are protected. Number two, what we<U+2019>ve consistently insisted on is that all parties involved <U+2013> whether it's members of Mr. Morsi's party or the opposition <U+2013> that they remain peaceful. And although we have not seen the kind of violence that many had feared so far, the potential remains there, and everybody has to show restraint..."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/01/remarks-president-obama-and-president-kikwete-tanzania-joint-press-confe|title=Remarks by President Obama and President Kikwete of Tanzania at Joint Press Conference|publisher=The White House|date=1 July 2013}}</ref> The US government put on high alert around five hundred crisis-response [[United States Marine Corps|marines]] who have been previously deployed in Italy and Spain in order to respond to the crisis in Egypt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stripes.com/news/us-marines-in-spain-italy-remain-on-heightened-alert-1.228618|title=US Marines in Spain, Italy remain on heightened alert|date=July 2, 2013|publisher=Stars and Stripes}}</ref>
;Others
* [[Human Rights Watch]] have alleged there that have been sexual assaults during the protests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2013/07/20137312315973608.html |title=Women sexually assaulted in Egypt protests |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date= 3 July 2013 |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2013/07/03/egypt-tahrir-square-women-sex-assaults.html |title=Mob rapes in Tahrir Square worry rights groups |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> In the first three days of the month, women's activists have reported 43 alleged sexual assaults of both foreign and domestic women.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anarchy in Egypt: Dutch reporter is 'raped in Tahrir Square' as MILLIONS take to the streets demanding president's resignation|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2352202/Anti-Morsi-protests-Tourists-warned-travelling-Egypt-seven-people-killed.html|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref>

